<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">38270126</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2024</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>26</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>18</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1080-6059</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>30</Volume><Issue>2</Issue><PubDate><Year>2023</Year><Month>Feb</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Emerging infectious diseases</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Emerg Infect Dis</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Power Law for Estimating Underdetection of Foodborne Disease Outbreaks, United States.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>337</StartPage><EndPage>340</EndPage><MedlinePgn>337-340</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.3201/eid3002.230342</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>We fit a power law distribution to US foodborne disease outbreaks to assess underdetection and underreporting. We predicted that 788 fewer than expected small outbreaks were identified annually during 1998-2017 and 365 fewer during 2018-2019, after whole-genome sequencing was implemented. Power law can help assess effectiveness of public health interventions.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ford</LastName><ForeName>Laura</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Self</LastName><ForeName>Julie L</ForeName><Initials>JL</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wong</LastName><ForeName>Karen K</ForeName><Initials>KK</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hoekstra</LastName><ForeName>Robert M</ForeName><Initials>RM</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Tauxe</LastName><ForeName>Robert V</ForeName><Initials>RV</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Rose</LastName><ForeName>Erica Billig</ForeName><Initials>EB</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>B